### Description

Currently when setting up XSRF protection in Angular, you can specify custom cookie and header names:
```ts
imports: [
  HttpClientModule,
  HttpClientXsrfModule.withOptions({
    cookieName: 'My-Xsrf-Cookie',
    headerName: 'My-Xsrf-Header',
  }),
],
```
but there is no way of getting/reading those configured values later on for usage withhin your own service/interceptor/component.

I can see that there are injection tokens defined for XSRF_COOKIE_NAME and XSRF_HEADER_NAME in Angular sources at https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/packages/common/http/src/xsrf.ts#L27C14-L27C31, but they dont seem to be exposed, because injecting them does not work:
```ts
import { XSRF_HEADER_NAME } from '@angular/common/http'; // ERROR: Module "@angular/common/http" has no exported member 'XSRF_HEADER_NAME'.ts(2305)
import { Inject, Injectable } from '@angular/core';

@Injectable()
export class MyService {
  public constructor(
    @Inject(XSRF_HEADER_NAME) private readonly _xsrfHeaderName: string,
  ) {}
}
```

### Proposed solution

Exppose `XSRF_COOKIE_NAME`  and `XSRF_HEADER_NAME` injection tokens, so they can be injected into service/interceptor/component.

### Alternatives considered

Its possible to create you own token and use that where needed, but its seems redundant, when XSRF cookie and header names are areleady set in angular.
Also if you want to use default Angular cookie/header name there is currently no way to get it programatically, you have to copy them from documentation. It would be handy if Angular somehow exposed its effective XSRF settings.

